WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.984 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.984 --> 00:00:03.472 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.472 --> 00:00:06.944 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.944 --> 00:00:10.420 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:11.570 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Good.

00:00:11.570 --> 00:00:12.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:18.220 align:middle line:84%
So last lecture, we
discussed Noether's theorem.

00:00:18.220 --> 00:00:22.510 align:middle line:84%
For every symmetry, for
every continuous symmetry,

00:00:22.510 --> 00:00:25.540 align:middle line:90%
there's a conserved current.

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:29.230 align:middle line:84%
And then we also started talking
about relativistic quantum

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:31.780 align:middle line:90%
mechanics.

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:36.370 align:middle line:84%
How we want to unify
special relativity

00:00:36.370 --> 00:00:37.990 align:middle line:90%
in quantum mechanics.

00:00:37.990 --> 00:00:40.840 align:middle line:84%
So the most immediate
idea for that

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.770 align:middle line:84%
is what's called the
relativistic quantum mechanics.

00:00:44.770 --> 00:00:49.300 align:middle line:84%
And the most immediate
generalization

00:00:49.300 --> 00:00:51.560 align:middle line:90%
of the Schrodinger equation--

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:52.480 align:middle line:90%
so if you have--

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:55.110 align:middle line:90%


00:00:55.110 --> 00:00:56.950 align:middle line:84%
so at the end of
last lecture, we

00:00:56.950 --> 00:00:59.950 align:middle line:84%
talked about, say, the most
immediate generalization

00:00:59.950 --> 00:01:05.010 align:middle line:84%
of the Schrodinger
equation, which--

00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:10.830 align:middle line:84%
so if I have E equal to,
say, p squared divided by 2m,

00:01:10.830 --> 00:01:16.410 align:middle line:84%
and then you go to
non-relativistic quantum

00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:17.985 align:middle line:90%
mechanics Schrodinger equation.

00:01:17.985 --> 00:01:22.070 align:middle line:90%


00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:24.500 align:middle line:84%
And now if you have
E squared equal to p

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:29.240 align:middle line:84%
squared plus m squared
for relativistic particle,

00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:31.790 align:middle line:84%
and then you get what's called
the Klein-Gordon equation.

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:38.610 align:middle line:90%


00:01:38.610 --> 00:01:41.580 align:middle line:84%
And again, this side
has the implication

00:01:41.580 --> 00:01:44.580 align:middle line:90%
of the wave function.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:47.620 align:middle line:84%
So this describe--
and then this--

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:50.100 align:middle line:84%
so as a generalization
of this, then

00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:53.395 align:middle line:84%
this means to
describe the quantum

00:01:53.395 --> 00:01:59.250 align:middle line:84%
mechanics of relativistic
free particle, say, of mass m,

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:01.470 align:middle line:90%
of mass m.

00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:09.930 align:middle line:84%
So here, the psi pi t,
x is the wave function

00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:11.249 align:middle line:90%
of a relativistic particle.

00:02:11.249 --> 00:02:17.150 align:middle line:90%


00:02:17.150 --> 00:02:22.550 align:middle line:90%
Relativistic particle of mass m.

00:02:22.550 --> 00:02:30.240 align:middle line:90%


00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.610 align:middle line:84%
And we also notice that
this equation actually

00:02:32.610 --> 00:02:37.560 align:middle line:84%
is the same as the simplest
field theory equation.

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:45.320 align:middle line:84%
So we also talked about a
simplest scalar field theory.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:45.980 align:middle line:90%
Classical.

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:49.460 align:middle line:90%
So here is a simple--

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:52.505 align:middle line:84%
a classic simplest
scalar field theory.

00:02:52.505 --> 00:02:56.640 align:middle line:90%


00:02:56.640 --> 00:03:02.385 align:middle line:84%
So this theory you can write
down the action of the form.

00:03:02.385 --> 00:03:09.850 align:middle line:90%


00:03:09.850 --> 00:03:14.490 align:middle line:84%
So this is the simplest
theory you can write down.

00:03:14.490 --> 00:03:17.310 align:middle line:84%
And then relativistic
environment theory.

00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:19.930 align:middle line:84%
And then the equation
of motion of this--

00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:23.250 align:middle line:84%
so this is-- you view
this as a classical field.

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:25.230 align:middle line:84%
And again, this has
the equation of motion

00:03:25.230 --> 00:03:29.550 align:middle line:84%
have exactly the same
form as this equation.

00:03:29.550 --> 00:03:34.590 align:middle line:84%
But now, here, phi, again,
is a function of t, x.

00:03:34.590 --> 00:03:37.510 align:middle line:84%
Now has a completely different
physical interpretation.

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:41.895 align:middle line:84%
So here is-- this is
a classical field.

00:03:41.895 --> 00:03:44.440 align:middle line:90%


00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:44.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:47.140 align:middle line:90%
So this is a classical field.

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:47.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:50.880 align:middle line:84%
So in this case,
the interpretation

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:56.310 align:middle line:84%
of the x in here, and in
here, it's very different.

00:03:56.310 --> 00:04:00.030 align:middle line:84%
So not only phi and the psi,
the physical interpretation

00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:01.045 align:middle line:90%
are different.

00:04:01.045 --> 00:04:03.420 align:middle line:84%
The physical interpretation
of x also here are different.

00:04:03.420 --> 00:04:05.400 align:middle line:90%
Here, x is just a label.

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:10.250 align:middle line:84%
Is a label for the
location in the space which

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:12.070 align:middle line:90%
we define this field.

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:14.820 align:middle line:84%
But here, the x
is the eigenvalue

00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:20.640 align:middle line:84%
of the position operator for
this relativistic particle.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:25.980 align:middle line:84%
And so they have very different
physical interpretation.

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:29.390 align:middle line:84%
And so let me just
label this equation by 1

00:04:29.390 --> 00:04:33.290 align:middle line:84%
and label this by 2
and this by 2 prime.

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:37.470 align:middle line:90%


00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:41.490 align:middle line:84%
So we also mentioned
that this one has--

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:44.070 align:middle line:84%
the interpretation of
this as the wave function

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:46.230 align:middle line:90%
for relativistic-- yeah, for--

00:04:46.230 --> 00:04:48.660 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so the equation for
relativistic quantum mechanics

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:50.160 align:middle line:90%
has a number of difficulties.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:58.040 align:middle line:90%


00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:06.040 align:middle line:84%
So the first is that, as you
will show in your pset 2,

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:08.170 align:middle line:90%
there's no sensible--

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:23.840 align:middle line:84%
no sensible way to define a
positive definite probability

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:25.370 align:middle line:90%
density.

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:33.260 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to interpret
this as a wave equation,

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:34.492 align:middle line:90%
then you must have a wave--

00:05:34.492 --> 00:05:36.200 align:middle line:84%
then you must have a
probability density,

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:38.390 align:middle line:84%
because in quantum
mechanics, probability

00:05:38.390 --> 00:05:41.560 align:middle line:90%
should be conserved.

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:45.970 align:middle line:84%
And the second difficulty is
that there's a negative energy

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:49.570 align:middle line:90%
state because of the square.

00:05:49.570 --> 00:05:51.430 align:middle line:84%
Because when you
take the square root,

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:54.370 align:middle line:84%
then you get the minus sign, and
then there's a negative energy

00:05:54.370 --> 00:06:01.540 align:middle line:84%
state, which you cannot avoid
in quantum mechanics even though

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:05.260 align:middle line:84%
classically you can just
throw them away by hand.

00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:13.050 align:middle line:84%
And the third thing we
mentioned at the end,

00:06:13.050 --> 00:06:17.670 align:middle line:84%
we said for a relativistic
wave equation,

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:23.660 align:middle line:84%
you can describe a fixed
number of particles.

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:29.320 align:middle line:90%


00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:32.050 align:middle line:84%
So the particle
number cannot change.

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:37.930 align:middle line:84%
So this equation describe
a single particle.

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:41.020 align:middle line:84%
And if you want to
describe two particles,

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:44.110 align:middle line:84%
then you need to write
down a separate equation

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:47.000 align:middle line:90%
for a different wave function.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.240 align:middle line:84%
So this is for the
two-particle wave function will

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:51.760 align:middle line:90%
be like this and et cetera.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:52.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:55.480 align:middle line:84%
But this does not
really make sense

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:58.480 align:middle line:84%
in the relativistic
system because we

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:03.710 align:middle line:84%
know that in the relativistic
system, E equal to mc square,

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:05.730 align:middle line:84%
in any case, you
have enough energy,

00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:08.150 align:middle line:84%
then you should be able
to create particles.

00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:11.480 align:middle line:84%
And then that means the number
of particles in the given

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:13.890 align:middle line:90%
process is not conserved.

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:16.670 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to use your
quantum mechanics to describe

00:07:16.670 --> 00:07:18.950 align:middle line:90%
a process, and then that--

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:22.220 align:middle line:84%
you cannot have a formalism,
which the number of particles

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:25.070 align:middle line:84%
is fixed, which
you cannot change.

00:07:25.070 --> 00:07:29.750 align:middle line:84%
And so this is actually the
most fundamental difficulty,

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:33.890 align:middle line:84%
is that you cannot change
the number of particles.

00:07:33.890 --> 00:07:39.900 align:middle line:84%
And related to this difficulty
is this interpretation.

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:42.930 align:middle line:84%
Here, we say-- now
if you want to--

00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:46.980 align:middle line:84%
we're saying here, there's
a fundamental asymmetry

00:07:46.980 --> 00:07:48.990 align:middle line:90%
between the t and x.

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:51.820 align:middle line:84%
Also, yeah, maybe
let me put it as 4,

00:07:51.820 --> 00:07:53.340 align:middle line:90%
there's also fundamental--

00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:56.040 align:middle line:90%


00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:57.890 align:middle line:84%
an additional
difficulty, there's

00:07:57.890 --> 00:08:08.055 align:middle line:84%
a fundamental asymmetry
between t and x.

00:08:08.055 --> 00:08:11.780 align:middle line:90%


00:08:11.780 --> 00:08:14.930 align:middle line:84%
So here, in the wave
equation, t is just

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:20.010 align:middle line:84%
a parameter, which will be
describing the evolution,

00:08:20.010 --> 00:08:28.110 align:middle line:84%
but the x is the eigenvalue
of quantum operators--

00:08:28.110 --> 00:08:30.750 align:middle line:84%
eigenvalues of
quantum operators.

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:33.570 align:middle line:90%
Say, corresponding to, say, hat.

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:37.030 align:middle line:84%
By putting a hat, we denote
the corresponding a quantum

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:37.530 align:middle line:90%
operator.

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:40.710 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so this is the eigenvalue
of position operators.

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:43.440 align:middle line:84%
And this asymmetry become
even more pronounced, say,

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:45.630 align:middle line:84%
if you can see
the two particles.

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:48.055 align:middle line:84%
You have two x's here,
but the only one t.

00:08:48.055 --> 00:08:48.555 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:48.555 --> 00:08:52.270 align:middle line:90%


00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:56.650 align:middle line:84%
So those-- because of those
fundamental difficulties--

00:08:56.650 --> 00:09:05.580 align:middle line:84%
so if you connect this
i to iv, so we conclude

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:13.630 align:middle line:84%
that the relativistic quantum
mechanics defined in the sense

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:15.640 align:middle line:84%
that you write down
a wave equation,

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:18.560 align:middle line:84%
and for wave
function, don't even--

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:23.736 align:middle line:90%
it does not-- that's not--

00:09:23.736 --> 00:09:31.338 align:middle line:84%
cannot be the
fundamental description.

00:09:31.338 --> 00:09:33.130 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, but relativistic
quantum mechanic

00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:34.880 align:middle line:84%
just refers to this
kind of wave equation.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:43.930 align:middle line:90%


00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:50.550 align:middle line:84%
So at most, this can be
approximated approximation

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:51.050 align:middle line:90%
at most.

00:09:51.050 --> 00:09:54.980 align:middle line:90%


00:09:54.980 --> 00:10:08.510 align:middle line:84%
This is approximate
description in situations, say,

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:16.280 align:middle line:84%
there's no particle
creation or annihilation.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:22.360 align:middle line:90%


00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:28.980 align:middle line:84%
So in case which your
particle number is fixed,

00:10:28.980 --> 00:10:32.250 align:middle line:84%
and then you can use
this as approximation,

00:10:32.250 --> 00:10:34.740 align:middle line:84%
but it cannot be a
fundamental description.

00:10:34.740 --> 00:10:37.860 align:middle line:84%
For example, later we will talk
about the fermionic version

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:39.130 align:middle line:90%
of this wave equation.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:41.970 align:middle line:84%
So this will describe a
particle without spin.

00:10:41.970 --> 00:10:45.300 align:middle line:84%
So later we will describe
the analogous equation

00:10:45.300 --> 00:10:49.260 align:middle line:84%
for electrons for spin
half, and then that

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:53.010 align:middle line:84%
can indeed be used to describe
the electron in a hydrogen atom

00:10:53.010 --> 00:10:57.220 align:middle line:84%
as far as you don't create
new electrons, et cetera.

00:10:57.220 --> 00:10:59.760 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so relativistic
quantum mechanics

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:01.590 align:middle line:84%
can only be described
as some kind of--

00:11:01.590 --> 00:11:04.170 align:middle line:84%
considered as an
approximate description.

00:11:04.170 --> 00:11:11.830 align:middle line:84%
But now if you want to unify
special relativity and quantum

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:15.560 align:middle line:84%
mechanics together, it turns
out that the right formulation

00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:18.390 align:middle line:90%
is just quantum field theory.

00:11:18.390 --> 00:11:24.750 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out that
the quantum field theory

00:11:24.750 --> 00:11:27.420 align:middle line:90%
addresses these difficulties.

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:37.130 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.130 --> 00:11:38.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:43.600 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out
that the right way--

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:46.560 align:middle line:84%
so if we want to describe
quantum mechanics,

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:49.950 align:middle line:84%
say, of relativistic
particles of mass m--

00:11:49.950 --> 00:11:55.080 align:middle line:84%
so we want to do here, it turns
out, the proper thing to do,

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:57.500 align:middle line:84%
which is a little bit
unintuitive at first sight,

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:01.400 align:middle line:84%
is to start with this field
theory, which seemingly have

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:03.260 align:middle line:84%
nothing to do with
relativistic particles,

00:12:03.260 --> 00:12:05.900 align:middle line:84%
but to start with this
classical field theory

00:12:05.900 --> 00:12:08.420 align:middle line:90%
and then quantize it.

00:12:08.420 --> 00:12:12.800 align:middle line:84%
It turns out, once you treat
this theory as a quantum field

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:15.560 align:middle line:84%
theory, and this
becomes a theory

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:18.380 align:middle line:84%
of arbitrary number of
relativistic particles

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:20.390 align:middle line:90%
of mass m.

00:12:20.390 --> 00:12:22.970 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the
non-intuitive part,

00:12:22.970 --> 00:12:27.410 align:middle line:84%
and that's one of the miracle,
say, of the field theory,

00:12:27.410 --> 00:12:31.820 align:middle line:84%
is that automatically gives
you a formalism for treating

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:35.090 align:middle line:90%
arbitrary number of particles.

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:36.965 align:middle line:90%
And yeah.

00:12:36.965 --> 00:12:41.100 align:middle line:90%


00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:43.350 align:middle line:90%
And also, in field theory--

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:47.550 align:middle line:84%
so both t and x are
parameters even though x only

00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:51.070 align:middle line:90%
labels your location.

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:53.700 align:middle line:84%
So both t and x are
parameters, and so you

00:12:53.700 --> 00:12:56.760 align:middle line:84%
can easily to make them
to be on equal ground

00:12:56.760 --> 00:12:59.778 align:middle line:84%
to be compatible with
special relativity.

00:12:59.778 --> 00:13:01.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:03.620 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:04.925 align:middle line:90%
So any questions on this?

00:13:04.925 --> 00:13:09.360 align:middle line:90%


00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:09.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:09.860 --> 00:13:13.020 align:middle line:84%
So we will see that the right
framework is quantum field

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:13.520 align:middle line:90%
theory.

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:15.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:19.640 align:middle line:84%
So finally, as a last motivation
for quantum field theory,

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:23.210 align:middle line:90%
we quickly describe the last--

00:13:23.210 --> 00:13:33.020 align:middle line:84%
so the field theory can
also arise at the limit

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:33.980 align:middle line:90%
of discrete systems.

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:44.410 align:middle line:90%


00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:49.613 align:middle line:84%
And this is the most relevant
for condensed matter physics.

00:13:49.613 --> 00:13:50.155 align:middle line:90%
For example--

00:13:50.155 --> 00:13:53.360 align:middle line:90%


00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:56.660 align:middle line:84%
So let's just
consider, say, some--

00:13:56.660 --> 00:14:00.290 align:middle line:84%
yeah, let's consider
8.03 example.

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:05.300 align:middle line:84%
So let's imagine you have
this number of particles,

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:09.650 align:middle line:84%
a number of the atoms,
say, on the chain.

00:14:09.650 --> 00:14:12.740 align:middle line:84%
And then they're connected
by some springs between them.

00:14:12.740 --> 00:14:15.960 align:middle line:90%


00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:18.750 align:middle line:90%
So this is the--

00:14:18.750 --> 00:14:21.330 align:middle line:84%
yeah, consider this
to be infinite.

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:26.430 align:middle line:84%
And the spacing between
them, say, is a.

00:14:26.430 --> 00:14:29.910 align:middle line:84%
So atom, I fixed on
some lattice points.

00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:33.930 align:middle line:90%
And the lattice spacing is a.

00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:38.080 align:middle line:90%
So yeah, so we can label the--

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:41.470 align:middle line:84%
say, each particle
by their position.

00:14:41.470 --> 00:14:45.220 align:middle line:84%
For example, this is x0, this
is x1, this is x2, et cetera.

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:45.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:47.770 align:middle line:84%
And and the typical
particle is xn.

00:14:47.770 --> 00:14:50.930 align:middle line:90%


00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:54.470 align:middle line:84%
At the location of a
n-th particle is xn.

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:59.000 align:middle line:84%
And so we can also
introduce the deviation

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.950 align:middle line:84%
between the equilibrium
position of each particle.

00:15:01.950 --> 00:15:04.250 align:middle line:90%
So let's call it eta n.

00:15:04.250 --> 00:15:06.440 align:middle line:84%
So now let's
consider the dynamics

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:09.420 align:middle line:90%
of eta n for this theory.

00:15:09.420 --> 00:15:11.930 align:middle line:84%
And so this is just a
deviation of the n-th particle

00:15:11.930 --> 00:15:13.720 align:middle line:90%
from its equilibrium position.

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:16.620 align:middle line:84%
So eta n 0 is
equilibrium position.

00:15:16.620 --> 00:15:21.150 align:middle line:84%
So now so now if you write down
the Lagrangian for this system,

00:15:21.150 --> 00:15:23.630 align:middle line:84%
so we can easily do, you
just write T minus V.

00:15:23.630 --> 00:15:29.550 align:middle line:84%
So T is the kinetic energy
and V is the potential energy.

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:36.050 align:middle line:84%
So we can just write it as
sum over n over all particles.

00:15:36.050 --> 00:15:38.240 align:middle line:84%
And then let's assume
they have the same mass,

00:15:38.240 --> 00:15:42.590 align:middle line:90%
let's write mu eta n dot square.

00:15:42.590 --> 00:15:44.630 align:middle line:84%
So this is a kinetic
term, so the mu

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:46.760 align:middle line:90%
is the mass for each particle.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:50.570 align:middle line:84%
And then their potential-- yeah,
let's assume at each point,

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.400 align:middle line:90%
there is also--

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:55.156 align:middle line:84%
yeah, let's just--
yeah, then there's

00:15:55.156 --> 00:15:58.310 align:middle line:84%
a interaction because each
particle are connected

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:03.020 align:middle line:84%
by the spring, and so
they are a harmonic force

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:08.260 align:middle line:90%
between neighboring particles.

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And now let's
imagine also there's

00:16:10.060 --> 00:16:15.400 align:middle line:84%
a harmonic potential which
trap this particle itself

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:17.950 align:middle line:90%
at each location.

00:16:17.950 --> 00:16:22.480 align:middle line:84%
So this is a very simple spring
and the particle problem which

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:25.900 align:middle line:90%
you encounter, say, in 8.03.

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:28.900 align:middle line:90%
Is this problem clear?

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:29.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:33.460 align:middle line:84%
I assume most of you have
seen this problem before.

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.100 align:middle line:84%
And your task in
8.03 is actually

00:16:36.100 --> 00:16:42.400 align:middle line:84%
to find the local modes,
say, of this system.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.220 align:middle line:84%
And in 8.03, you also
described that we can--

00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:48.320 align:middle line:90%
and a go to zero limit.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:51.530 align:middle line:84%
So if the lattice
spacing is very small.

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:54.250 align:middle line:84%
And if we are only
interested in the behavior

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:56.410 align:middle line:84%
of the system at a
very large distance,

00:16:56.410 --> 00:16:58.870 align:middle line:84%
say the distance is much
larger than a equals to--

00:16:58.870 --> 00:17:02.020 align:middle line:84%
much larger than a, then you can
essentially treat this system

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:02.950 align:middle line:90%
as a continuum.

00:17:02.950 --> 00:17:05.690 align:middle line:84%
You don't have to resolve
individual particles.

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:07.150 align:middle line:90%
And so we can just--

00:17:07.150 --> 00:17:08.740 align:middle line:90%
equal to newer limit.

00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:17.970 align:middle line:84%
So it can be true to the chain
as a continuum of particles.

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:28.030 align:middle line:90%


00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:36.430 align:middle line:84%
And so each eta n t, you
replace it by eta x, t.

00:17:36.430 --> 00:17:40.090 align:middle line:90%
So x label is position.

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:43.420 align:middle line:84%
So x label is position,
t describe the dynamics.

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:47.500 align:middle line:84%
So eta is the deviation
at the location x,

00:17:47.500 --> 00:17:49.090 align:middle line:90%
and it's depend on t.

00:17:49.090 --> 00:17:51.280 align:middle line:90%
So this is the oscillator.

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:56.830 align:middle line:84%
And then sum over n
in the Lagrangian,

00:17:56.830 --> 00:18:02.480 align:middle line:84%
then we can replace it
by integral over dx.

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:06.440 align:middle line:84%
And now you just treat this as
a one-dimensional continuum.

00:18:06.440 --> 00:18:08.930 align:middle line:90%
So integration over dx.

00:18:08.930 --> 00:18:13.430 align:middle line:84%
But of course, here, there's
a label-- a lattice spacing,

00:18:13.430 --> 00:18:18.740 align:middle line:84%
so the so the infinitesimal
here, the element is a.

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:23.560 align:middle line:84%
The a times the sum over n,
you can replace it by dx.

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:26.250 align:middle line:90%


00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:28.530 align:middle line:90%
That is the lattice spacing.

00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:31.560 align:middle line:84%
And now you can just
write this Lagrangian

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:35.160 align:middle line:90%
in terms of continuum theory.

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:36.660 align:middle line:84%
Now you can write
this Lagrangian

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:41.170 align:middle line:84%
in terms of continuum theory,
and then let's just do it.

00:18:41.170 --> 00:18:44.540 align:middle line:84%
So we can write it-- yeah, let
me just write one more step.

00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:46.720 align:middle line:84%
So you can write
it as sum over a.

00:18:46.720 --> 00:18:49.930 align:middle line:84%
We take the a factor out
because the a factor out has

00:18:49.930 --> 00:18:52.900 align:middle line:90%
to be changing to integration.

00:18:52.900 --> 00:18:57.370 align:middle line:84%
And then you have 1/2
mu divided by a eta n

00:18:57.370 --> 00:19:01.410 align:middle line:90%
squared minus 1/2 lambda a.

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:06.930 align:middle line:90%


00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:14.910 align:middle line:84%
So I just slightly
rewrite this Lagrangian

00:19:14.910 --> 00:19:18.180 align:middle line:84%
so that it's easy to
take the continuum limit.

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:23.780 align:middle line:84%
So we have taken the factor
of a out, but for this term,

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:26.210 align:middle line:84%
because this concerns the
difference between the two,

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:29.240 align:middle line:84%
and we also divided by
a in the downstairs,

00:19:29.240 --> 00:19:31.340 align:middle line:84%
and then we need to
multiply a upstairs,

00:19:31.340 --> 00:19:33.860 align:middle line:90%
and then there's a in the front.

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:37.143 align:middle line:84%
And now the continuum
limit, you can just

00:19:37.143 --> 00:19:38.310 align:middle line:90%
replace this by an integral.

00:19:38.310 --> 00:19:41.080 align:middle line:90%


00:19:41.080 --> 00:19:41.880 align:middle line:90%
And now I just--

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:44.890 align:middle line:90%


00:19:44.890 --> 00:19:50.230 align:middle line:84%
can just write it as 1/2
mu tilde eta dot squared.

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:55.680 align:middle line:84%
So now eta n just
replaced by eta x, t.

00:19:55.680 --> 00:19:59.930 align:middle line:84%
And here, let me
call it lambda tilde.

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:02.150 align:middle line:90%
Partial x eta square.

00:20:02.150 --> 00:20:03.740 align:middle line:84%
And this term, you
can just replace it

00:20:03.740 --> 00:20:05.600 align:middle line:90%
by the derivative of eta.

00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:09.590 align:middle line:84%
And then this has just become
1/2 sigma tilde eta square.

00:20:09.590 --> 00:20:12.320 align:middle line:90%


00:20:12.320 --> 00:20:18.050 align:middle line:84%
And the mu tilde, of
course, is mu divided by a.

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:21.500 align:middle line:90%
Lambda tilde is lambda times a.

00:20:21.500 --> 00:20:29.830 align:middle line:84%
And sigma tilde, this
is sigma divided by a.

00:20:29.830 --> 00:20:32.920 align:middle line:84%
So the continuum limit is that
this quantity has to be fixed.

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:34.940 align:middle line:84%
The tilde, the quantity
has to be fixed.

00:20:34.940 --> 00:20:37.850 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a
continuum Lagrangian.

00:20:37.850 --> 00:20:40.140 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a
classical field theory.

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:47.480 align:middle line:84%
And this theory is essentially
the same as that theory.

00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:52.230 align:middle line:84%
So if you take this
factor mu tilde out,

00:20:52.230 --> 00:20:56.560 align:middle line:84%
if we take this
vector mu tilde out--

00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:58.370 align:middle line:84%
so let me just take
this factor of mu

00:20:58.370 --> 00:21:02.210 align:middle line:84%
tilde out in the front,
just up to a wall factor.

00:21:02.210 --> 00:21:05.470 align:middle line:84%
And here is lambda tilde
divided by mu tilde.

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:08.700 align:middle line:84%
We call it-- let's
call it v square.

00:21:08.700 --> 00:21:12.000 align:middle line:84%
And this becomes sigma
tilde divided by mu tilde,

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.030 align:middle line:90%
let's call it m squared.

00:21:14.030 --> 00:21:20.510 align:middle line:84%
So the V squared is equal to
mu tilde is equal to the lambda

00:21:20.510 --> 00:21:27.530 align:middle line:84%
tilde divided by mu tilde, and
m squared is equal to sigma

00:21:27.530 --> 00:21:29.180 align:middle line:90%
tilde squared by mu tilde.

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:31.960 align:middle line:90%


00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:33.760 align:middle line:84%
And then this is
just essentially

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:39.790 align:middle line:84%
identical to that theory
when V equal to 1.

00:21:39.790 --> 00:21:47.900 align:middle line:84%
So when V equal to 1,
become the same, is just 2,

00:21:47.900 --> 00:21:49.833 align:middle line:90%
the equation 2.

00:21:49.833 --> 00:21:51.500 align:middle line:84%
So we could do, of
course, corresponding

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:53.810 align:middle line:84%
to relativistic
case, speed of light,

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:57.560 align:middle line:84%
but in general, this
describe-- can-- yeah.

00:21:57.560 --> 00:22:02.000 align:middle line:84%
This can describe--
but in general, this

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:03.610 align:middle line:84%
is a non-relativistic--
in general,

00:22:03.610 --> 00:22:05.360 align:middle line:84%
this can be just a
long relativistic field

00:22:05.360 --> 00:22:09.620 align:middle line:90%
theory for other values of V.

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:15.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- so even though
this example is very simple,

00:22:15.770 --> 00:22:21.170 align:middle line:84%
but this is actually a very
general way that we can treat

00:22:21.170 --> 00:22:25.370 align:middle line:84%
many condensed matter systems,
which often involve a lattice,

00:22:25.370 --> 00:22:28.910 align:middle line:84%
say, because the solid, you
can imagine all the atoms are

00:22:28.910 --> 00:22:30.390 align:middle line:90%
on the lattice, et cetera.

00:22:30.390 --> 00:22:35.460 align:middle line:84%
And if you're only interested in
the very macroscopic behavior,

00:22:35.460 --> 00:22:39.260 align:middle line:84%
then you can treat
solid as a continuum.

00:22:39.260 --> 00:22:42.650 align:middle line:84%
And now you can now if you're
interested in the mechanics

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:45.650 align:middle line:84%
of such a system, then the
quantum field theory then

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:46.670 align:middle line:90%
naturally arises.

00:22:46.670 --> 00:22:47.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:47.170 --> 00:22:50.580 align:middle line:90%


00:22:50.580 --> 00:22:51.080 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:22:51.080 --> 00:22:52.915 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this example?

00:22:52.915 --> 00:22:56.620 align:middle line:90%


00:22:56.620 --> 00:22:57.750 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

