quantization condition.

00:41:13.620 --> 00:41:16.490 align:middle line:90%
So this is just equal to i.

00:41:16.490 --> 00:41:21.980 align:middle line:84%
So the standard-- so if you
plug in the expression for x

00:41:21.980 --> 00:41:23.120 align:middle line:90%
and the t--

00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:31.960 align:middle line:84%
and the p into here, and then
you find that a and a dagger,

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:33.520 align:middle line:90%
the commutator is equal to 1.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:38.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is your familiar
creation and annihilation

00:41:38.110 --> 00:41:42.400 align:middle line:84%
operator for
harmonic oscillator.

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:44.600 align:middle line:90%
For harmonic oscillator.

00:41:44.600 --> 00:41:50.410 align:middle line:84%
And now, we can also use the
a to build the Hilbert space

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:55.020 align:middle line:84%
because a are the-- yeah,
because all your operator now--

00:41:55.020 --> 00:41:57.150 align:middle line:90%
because x and p--

00:41:57.150 --> 00:42:00.210 align:middle line:84%
x and the p are expressed
in terms of a and a dagger.

00:42:00.210 --> 00:42:02.730 align:middle line:84%
So essentially, any
operator of this theory

00:42:02.730 --> 00:42:04.950 align:middle line:84%
