Good, OK.

00:43:10.385 --> 00:43:12.890 align:middle line:90%


00:43:12.890 --> 00:43:16.720 align:middle line:90%
So let me just summarize.

00:43:16.720 --> 00:43:20.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is very, very
familiar, but let's summarize

00:43:20.950 --> 00:43:22.780 align:middle line:90%
the rule we have been using.

00:43:22.780 --> 00:43:31.310 align:middle line:84%
Summarize the steps in context
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:43:31.310 --> 00:43:34.090 align:middle line:84%
And then the same
steps can be used

00:43:34.090 --> 00:43:38.750 align:middle line:90%
to quantize the field theory.

00:43:38.750 --> 00:43:41.380 align:middle line:90%
Steps of quantization.

00:43:41.380 --> 00:43:46.070 align:middle line:90%


00:43:46.070 --> 00:43:48.540 align:middle line:90%
So we make it a general.

00:43:48.540 --> 00:43:54.920 align:middle line:84%
So first-- so the 0 step is
that the classical equation

00:43:54.920 --> 00:44:00.175 align:middle line:84%
of motion becomes a
quantum operator equation.

00:44:00.175 --> 00:44:03.040 align:middle line:90%


00:44:03.040 --> 00:44:07.690 align:middle line:84%
Then the first step is to find
the most general solution--

00:44:07.690 --> 00:44:17.050 align:middle line:90%


00:44:17.050 --> 00:44:35.950 align:middle line:84%
to find the most
general solution

00:44:35.950 --> 00:44:38.925 align:middle line:84%
to classical
equation of motion--

00:44:38.925 --> 00:44:40.300 align:middle line:84%
yeah, just to
equation of motion.

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:43.150 align:middle line:90%


00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:50.760 align:middle line:84%
And then you go to
quantum, and then you

00:44:50.760 --> 00:45:01.764 align:middle line:84%
just promote the
integration constants

00:45:01.764 --> 00:45:08.030 align:middle line:84%
in your classical
solution in 1, in step 1

00:45:08.030 --> 00:45:11.690 align:middle line:90%
to constant operators--

00:45:11.690 --> 00:45:14.360 align:middle line:90%


00:45:14.360 --> 00:45:15.960 align:middle line:90%
constant quantum operators.

00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:19.510 align:middle line:90%


00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:21.580 align:middle line:90%
So this gives the--

00:45:21.580 --> 00:45:31.470 align:middle line:84%
then you have the full-time
evolution at the quantum level.

00:45:31.470 --> 00:45:37.210 align:middle line:90%


00:45:37.210 --> 00:45:42.680 align:middle line:84%
Now you know how the
quantum operator evolves.

00:45:42.680 --> 00:46:03.610 align:middle line:84%
And then you impose canonical
quantization conditions.

00:46:03.610 --> 00:46:07.870 align:middle line:90%


00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:10.930 align:middle line:84%
So that will tell
you the commutators

00:46:10.930 --> 00:46:15.790 align:middle line:84%
between those integration
constant operators

00:46:15.790 --> 00:46:19.210 align:middle line:90%
just as we do here.

00:46:19.210 --> 00:46:45.350 align:middle line:84%
And then constant
operators in 2,

00:46:45.350 --> 00:46:48.020 align:middle line:84%
now you know also the
commutation relation

00:46:48.020 --> 00:46:48.830 align:middle line:90%
between them--

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:50.930 align:middle line:84%
among them, and
then now can be used

00:46:50.930 --> 00:46:58.250 align:middle line:90%
to generate the Hilbert space.

00:46:58.250 --> 00:47:09.310 align:middle line:90%


00:47:09.310 --> 00:47:10.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:10.600 --> 00:47:15.120 align:middle line:84%
So this step 1 to
4 are very general.

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:19.950 align:middle line:84%
And if you can do it, and then
you can essentially do it--

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:23.320 align:middle line:90%
apply it to any system.

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:25.612 align:middle line:84%
Say one-- harmonic oscillator
is one degree of freedom,

00:47:25.612 --> 00:47:28.112 align:middle line:84%
you can apply it two degrees
freedom, three degrees freedom.

00:47:28.112 --> 00:47:30.190 align:middle line:84%
And also to field theory,
infinite number degrees

00:47:30.190 --> 00:47:31.970 align:middle line:90%
of freedom.

00:47:31.970 --> 00:47:33.890 align:middle line:84%
And now we will apply
these to field theory.

00:47:33.890 --> 00:47:34.520 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

